"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-9-10.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/matthew.json (pre-existing: 9:6)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch. 9 healing clusters: classified as fulfillment (Isa 35; 53:4) and direct revelation
  where the Son of Man title is used with explicit authority claims
- "Son of David" healings (9:27): classified as direct — messianic title acknowledged
- Bridegroom metaphor (9:15): classified as direct — explicit self-identification
- New cloth/new wineskins (9:16-17): classified as revelation of God — the new covenant
  era Christ inaugurates cannot be contained in old structures
- Mission discourse (ch. 10): classified largely as direct teaching and revelation of God
  — Christ sending the twelve mirrors YHWH's prophetic commission; "he who receives you
  receives me" (10:40) is the strongest identification
- 10:34 ("not peace but sword"): revelation of God — the eschatological division Christ
  brings is the fulfillment of Mic 7:6 and the crisis of the kingdom
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus crosses back to "his own city" (Capernaum) — the geography positions him as the one who moves between regions at will, without being contained by any single place. The boat-crossing recalls the stilling of the storm (8:23-27) and the Gadarene mission; the return structures the healing cycle around his authority. The gathering of a paralytic before him anticipates the eschatological gathering before the throne of the Son of Man (25:31-32).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "And behold, some people brought to him a paralytic, lying on a bed. And when Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic, \'Take heart, my son; your sins are forgiven.\'" The forgiveness of sins before the healing establishes the priority: the paralysis is the symptom; sin is the root condition. In the OT, forgiveness of sins is a divine prerogative (Isa 43:25; Ps 103:3; Mic 7:18). Jesus speaks forgiveness directly, on his own authority, not as a mediator invoking YHWH\'s mercy but as the one who forgives. The Christological claim is embedded in the structure of his speech.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "And behold, some of the scribes said to themselves, \'This man is blaspheming.\'" The scribes correctly identify the claim Jesus is making — forgiveness of sins is God\'s prerogative — but draw the wrong conclusion. Blasphemy requires that the claim be false; if Jesus is the Son of God, the forgiveness is genuine and the charge is wrong. Their accusation is the clearest recognition in the passage of what Jesus is claiming, even if they deny the claim. They understand him better than the crowds who simply marvel at the miracle.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation: "But Jesus, knowing their thoughts, said, \'Why do you think evil in your hearts?\'" The knowledge of unspoken thoughts (<em>enthymēseis</em>) is a divine attribute in the OT: YHWH alone searches the heart (Jer 17:10; Ps 139:1-4; 1 Sam 16:7). Jesus\' access to the scribes\' unspoken reasoning is a quiet theophanic detail embedded in the confrontation — his authority to forgive and his authority to know the heart stand together as evidence of his identity.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "For which is easier, to say, \'Your sins are forgiven,\' or to say, \'Rise and walk\'?" The rhetorical question exposes the logic of the demonstration: words of forgiveness are invisible and unverifiable; the command "rise and walk" has an immediate visible outcome. Jesus will use the visible to authenticate the invisible. The double authority — over sin and over physical paralysis — mirrors the Isaianic vision of the Servant who both heals and forgives (Isa 53:4-5).</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And he rose and went home." The instantaneous response to Jesus\' word — the paralytic rises and walks — fulfills the promise of Isa 35:3-6 ("Then shall the lame man leap like a deer") and echoes Ps 107:20 ("He sent out his word and healed them"). The healed man going to his home is both a practical detail and a theological one: the forgiven, restored man returns to ordinary life as the sign that salvation restores rather than removes from the world.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the crowds saw it, they were afraid, and they glorified God, who had given such authority to men." The crowds\' response — fear and glorification of God — is the correct theophanic response. Their characterization "given such authority to men" reflects the Danielic Son of Man language (Dan 7:14: authority given to one like a son of man) without grasping its full Christological weight. The crowds worship God but have not yet identified the one through whom God acts. The Gospel moves toward that identification.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "As Jesus passed on from there, he saw a man called Matthew sitting at the tax collector\'s booth, and he said to him, \'Follow me.\' And he rose and followed him." The call of Matthew (a tax collector — collaborator with Rome, ritually unclean through contact with Gentile coinage) mirrors the calls of 4:18-22 in structure: "Follow me" → immediate response. The one who commands follows from Peter and Andrew is now commanding a man excluded from normal Jewish religious life. The scope of the call is already beginning to widen beyond the respectable.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "And as Jesus reclined at table in the house, behold, many tax collectors and sinners came and were reclining with Jesus and his disciples." Table fellowship with tax collectors and sinners in the ancient world was not merely social tolerance but a covenant act — sharing food implied acceptance, solidarity, and social identification. Jesus\' practice of open table fellowship is the enacted proclamation of the kingdom\'s inclusive character. It is the shadow of the eschatological banquet (8:11; 22:1-14) available now, ahead of time, to those the religious establishment excluded.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when the Pharisees saw this, they said to his disciples, \'Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?\'" The Pharisees\' question is addressed to the disciples, not to Jesus — a social distancing maneuver. Their objection reflects the purity logic that holiness is maintained by separation from the impure. Jesus\' response inverts the logic: the holy does not withdraw from the impure but cleanses it by contact. This is the Incarnation principle operating at the level of table fellowship.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "But when he heard it, he said, \'Those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick.\'" The physician metaphor identifies Jesus as the one who comes to heal — specifically those who know they are sick, not those who consider themselves healthy. The Christological bearing: the messianic mission is directed toward the lost and the broken (Isa 61:1; Luke 4:18-19). The "well" who do not need a physician are those who have not yet recognized their condition — the greater irony in the Sermon\'s context (5:20: "unless your righteousness exceeds that of the scribes and Pharisees").</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "Go and learn what this means: \'I desire mercy, and not sacrifice.\' For I came not to call the righteous but sinners." The citation of Hos 6:6 ("I desire steadfast love and not sacrifice") is Jesus\' self-authorization for his table fellowship practice. The phrase "I came" (<em>ēlthon</em>) is the language of divine mission — the same construction used in 5:17 ("I came not to abolish but to fulfill"). The purpose of the coming is the calling of sinners: the mission is not confirmation of the worthy but rescue of the lost.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then the disciples of John came to him, saying, \'Why do we and the Pharisees fast, but your disciples do not fast?\'" The question about fasting identifies the tension between the penitential practices of the old era and the celebratory character of the new. John\'s disciples (who had heard John announce the coming kingdom) and the Pharisees (who observed fasting as covenant discipline) both practice mourning-fasting; Jesus\' disciples do not. The reason is Christological: the kingdom has arrived in the person of the king.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus said to them, \'Can the wedding guests mourn as long as the bridegroom is with them? The days will come when the bridegroom is taken away from them, and then they will fast.\'" The bridegroom is a direct messianic self-identification. In the OT, YHWH is the bridegroom of Israel (Isa 54:5; 62:5; Hos 2:16-20); Jesus appropriates this image for himself. The present time is the wedding feast — fasting would be inappropriate. The "days when the bridegroom is taken away" directly predicts the passion. The verse is one of Matthew\'s most explicit Christological self-disclosures before the confession at Caesarea Philippi.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "No one puts a piece of unshrunk cloth on an old garment, for the patch tears away from the garment, and a worse tear is made." The new cloth / old garment parable announces that the kingdom Jesus brings is not a repair to existing structures but a new creation. The Christological application: the covenant inaugurated in Christ is the new garment of Isa 61:10 ("he has clothed me with the garments of salvation, he has covered me with the robe of righteousness"), not a patch on the Mosaic order.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Neither is new wine put into old wineskins. If it is, the skins burst and the wine is spilled and the skins are destroyed. But new wine is put into fresh wineskins, and so both are preserved." The new wine of the kingdom requires new containers. The eschatological wine of Isa 25:6 ("well-aged wine, wine well refined") and the Messianic banquet cannot be held in the existing institutional structures. This anticipates the church as the new community formed around Christ — a new wineskin appropriate for the wine of the Spirit poured out at Pentecost (Acts 2:13-17).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A shadow: "While he was saying these things to them, behold, a ruler came in and knelt before him, saying, \'My daughter has just died, but come and lay your hand on her, and she will live.\'" The raising of the dead — here anticipated in the ruler\'s faith before the act — echoes Elijah\'s raising of the widow\'s son (1 Kgs 17:17-24) and Elisha\'s raising of the Shunammite\'s son (2 Kgs 4:32-37). The pattern is: the prophet comes, lays on hands, the child lives. Jesus will fulfill and exceed this pattern.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "And Jesus rose and followed him, with his disciples." The deliberate following of the ruler to his home — Jesus going where the need is — mirrors the pattern of divine condescension in the OT. YHWH descends to hear the cry of his people (Exod 3:7-8); Jesus rises and follows. The disciples following Jesus as he follows the ruler shows the shape of discipleship: following the one who goes ahead into every place of need and death.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A fulfillment: "And behold, a woman who had suffered from a discharge of blood for twelve years came up behind him and touched the fringe of his garment." The woman\'s twelve-year hemorrhage rendered her ritually unclean (Lev 15:25-27), excluded from the covenant community, untouchable. She touches Jesus from behind — in the crowd, without permission. The Christological pattern: the unclean touching the holy should defile the holy; instead the holy cleanses the unclean. This is the incarnation logic, applied in miniature at every healing.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "For she said to herself, \'If I only touch his garment, I will be made well.\'" Her faith is specifically in the power resident in Jesus — not in a general hope for divine healing but in the specific conviction that this person, Jesus, is the source of life and healing. The fringe (<em>kraspedon</em>) of his garment may allude to the tassels commanded in Num 15:38-40 as reminders of the commandments; if so, the woman reaches for the covenant promise embodied in the one who wears it.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus turned, and seeing her he said, \'Take heart, daughter; your faith has made you well.\' And instantly the woman was made well." The double movement — Jesus perceiving the touch and turning to address her — shows him as fully attentive to the one who reached for him in faith. The commendation "your faith has made you well" grants her an active role; the healing is not merely something done to her but a transaction in which her faith participates. This models the response the Gospel calls for throughout.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A shadow: "And when Jesus came to the ruler\'s house and saw the flute players and the crowd making a commotion." The formal mourning ritual (professional flute players were hired at deaths) is already underway — the death is established as real and the social response as complete. Jesus entering this scene of formal mourning echoes the pattern of Elisha at the Shunammite\'s house (2 Kgs 4:33), where the prophet cleared the room before the raising. The clearing of the mourners is an assertion of authority over the situation.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said, \'Go away, for the girl is not dead but sleeping.\' And they laughed at him." The dismissal of death as sleep (<em>katheudei</em>) is a Christological claim: what is death from the perspective of human mortality is sleep from the perspective of the one who has power over it. Jesus uses the same word for Lazarus (John 11:11-14) and it appears in Paul\'s usage (1 Thess 4:13-14). The crowd\'s laughter is the natural response to what sounds like denial of evident reality; it intensifies the dramatic irony of the raising to follow.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "But when the crowd had been put outside, he went in and took her by the hand, and the girl arose." The raising of Jairus\'s daughter is one of three resurrections before the cross (alongside the widow\'s son at Nain, Luke 7:11-17, and Lazarus, John 11). The touch and the arising directly echo Elijah (1 Kgs 17:21-22) and Elisha (2 Kgs 4:34-35) but surpass them: the prophets prayed to YHWH for the restoration; Jesus acts on his own authority, by his own word and touch. The shadow becomes direct revelation.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the report of this went through all that district." The spread of the report mirrors the prophetic tradition: YHWH\'s mighty acts spread through the nations (Josh 2:10; Ps 22:27-28). Matthew records the growing fame of Jesus as the accumulation of evidence that the kingdom of God is present in his person and ministry. The healings and raisings are not isolated wonders but signs pointing to the identity of the one who performs them.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And as Jesus passed on from there, two blind men followed him, crying aloud, \'Have mercy on us, Son of David.\'" "Son of David" is the primary messianic title in Jewish expectation, rooted in 2 Sam 7:12-16 and elaborated in Ps 72; Isa 11. The cry of the blind for healing from the Son of David directly fulfills Isa 35:5 ("then the eyes of the blind shall be opened"). The blind men perceive — through non-visual faith — what sighted observers miss: the identity of Jesus as the promised Davidic Messiah.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "When he entered the house, the blind men came to him, and Jesus said to them, \'Do you believe that I am able to do this?\' They said to him, \'Yes, Lord.\'" Jesus requires an explicit faith-confession before the healing — not as a formula but as a genuine question: do they believe in his specific authority? The double use of "Lord" (<em>Kyrie</em>) by the blind men throughout their approach (v.27-28) gives their confession its weight: they address the Son of David with the divine title, collapsing the messianic and divine registers.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then he touched their eyes, saying, \'According to your faith be it done to you.\'" The touch of the eyes recalls the Isaianic vision of the Servant who "opens the eyes that are blind" (Isa 42:7). The faith-proportionality principle ("according to your faith") does not make faith the mechanism of healing but positions faith as the appropriate receptive posture toward the one who heals. The healing vindicates the blind men\'s confession that Jesus is the Son of David able to restore sight.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "And their eyes were opened. And Jesus sternly warned them, \'See that no one knows about it.\'" The instruction to silence after a healing — repeated throughout chs. 8-9 — reflects the "messianic secret" pattern. Jesus is managing the pace and nature of his public disclosure; premature announcement of healing miracles risks reducing him to a wonder-worker rather than allowing the full revelation of his identity through teaching, death, and resurrection. The secret cannot be kept (v.31), but the instruction reveals his deliberate control of his own proclamation.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "But they went away and spread his fame through all that district." The inability of the healed to remain silent mirrors the prophetic pattern: when God acts, his acts cannot be contained (Jer 20:9: "If I say, \'I will not mention him, or speak any more in his name,\' there is in my heart as it were a burning fire"). The spreading fame is a structural feature of the Matthean narrative: the kingdom\'s presence cannot be suppressed despite the attempts to manage its disclosure.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A fulfillment: "As they were going away, behold, a demon-oppressed man who was mute was brought to him." The mute demoniac immediately follows the blind men — Matthew pairs miracle-types to demonstrate the scope of messianic restoration. The blind see (v.30) and the mute will speak (v.33), fulfilling Isa 35:5-6 ("the eyes of the blind shall be opened... and the tongue of the mute sing for joy"). Matthew\'s healing narrative in chs. 8-9 is a deliberate mosaic of Isaianic fulfillment-signs.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And when the demon had been cast out, the mute man spoke. And the crowds marveled, saying, \'Never was anything like this seen in Israel.\'" The crowds\' verdict — "never was anything like this seen in Israel" — is a direct claim of uniqueness. Unlike the Elijah and Elisha healing narratives, which had OT precedents, the scope and character of Jesus\' ministry surpasses anything in Israel\'s prophetic tradition. The comparison is with all of Israel\'s history, positioning Jesus not as the next in a line of prophets but as a singular figure.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "But the Pharisees said, \'He casts out demons by the prince of demons.\'" The counter-charge — that Jesus\' authority comes from Beelzebul rather than from God — is the theological opposition that will be developed in 12:22-32 (the Beelzebul controversy and the unforgivable sin). The Pharisees correctly identify that the authority is real and extraordinary but attribute it to the wrong source. The irony is that the true source is the Holy Spirit (12:28: "it is by the Spirit of God that I cast out demons"), and their attribution to Satan is the specific blasphemy Jesus will warn against.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And Jesus went throughout all the cities and villages, teaching in their synagogues and proclaiming the gospel of the kingdom and healing every disease and every affliction." The summary of Jesus\' ministry — teaching, proclaiming, healing — fulfills Isa 61:1-2 (the Servant\'s commission: to bring good news to the poor, healing to the brokenhearted) and Isa 35:5-6 (healing signs of the messianic age). Matthew uses this summary formula (cf. 4:23) to frame the teaching and healing cycles as a unified messianic mission.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "When he saw the crowds, he had compassion for them, because they were harassed and helpless, like sheep without a shepherd." The compassion of Jesus for the scattered sheep fulfills and embodies the divine promise in Ezek 34:11-16, where YHWH declares he will himself be the shepherd of the scattered flock, seeking the lost, healing the sick, and binding up the injured. Jesus is the fulfillment of YHWH\'s shepherding promise — the divine shepherd who has come to his sheep in person.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then he said to his disciples, \'The harvest is plentiful, but the laborers are few.\'" The harvest metaphor for divine judgment and restoration pervades the prophets (Isa 27:12; Joel 3:13; Jer 51:33). Jesus reframes the harvest as primarily a gathering rather than a judgment — the plentiful harvest is the crowds who are ready to receive the kingdom. The "laborers" the harvest Lord sends are the twelve; their commissioning immediately follows. Christ is the Lord of the harvest who sends and also who harvests.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "Therefore pray earnestly to the Lord of the harvest to send out laborers into his harvest." The instruction to pray to the "Lord of the harvest" (<em>kyrion tou therismou</em>) is addressed to the disciples who immediately become the answer to their own prayer (10:1-5). The Christological bearing: Jesus both teaches the disciples to pray to the Father for laborers and is himself the one who commissions the laborers in ch. 10. He is simultaneously the one who sends the prayer and the one through whom it is answered.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "And he called to him his twelve disciples and gave them authority over unclean spirits, to cast them out, and to heal every disease and every affliction." The delegation of authority to the twelve mirrors the pattern of prophetic commissioning (Moses commissioning Joshua, Num 27:18-20; Elijah commissioning Elisha, 1 Kgs 19:19-21). But Jesus gives authority on his own — not invoking YHWH\'s name but giving from his own store. The authority over unclean spirits and disease is the same authority he has exercised in chs. 8-9, now extended to those who follow him.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "The names of the twelve apostles are these: first, Simon, who is called Peter, and Andrew his brother; James the son of Zebedee, and John his brother." The naming of the twelve echoes the naming of the twelve tribes of Israel (Gen 35:22-26; 49:1-28) and will be fulfilled in the eschatological statement of 19:28 ("you who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel"). The twelve constitute a new Israel around the new Moses — the reconstitution of the covenant people around Christ.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "Philip and Bartholomew; Thomas and Matthew the tax collector; James the son of Alphaeus, and Thaddaeus." The list includes Matthew identified as "the tax collector" — his former profession named as the marker of grace: one who was excluded from normal Jewish religious life is now numbered among the reconstituted twelve. The inclusion of Matthew alongside men of more respectable backgrounds is the enacted proclamation of 9:13 ("I came not to call the righteous but sinners").</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "Simon the Zealot, and Judas Iscariot, who betrayed him." The list ends with the betrayer — a shadow cast over the commissioning from the start. The inclusion of Judas among the twelve is the deepest expression of the scandal of election: the one who betrayed the Son of God was among those given authority to heal and cast out demons in his name. The tension between genuine commission and ultimate apostasy will be resolved only at the Last Supper and the passion.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "These twelve Jesus sent out, instructing them, \'Go nowhere among the Gentiles and enter no town of the Samaritans, but go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel.\'" The restriction to Israel in the first mission is the "Jew first" pattern (Rom 1:16) that characterizes the ministry until the resurrection. The "lost sheep of the house of Israel" echoes Ezek 34:16 (YHWH seeking the lost sheep) and 34:11 (the divine shepherd gathering the scattered). Jesus now sends the twelve as extensions of his own shepherding mission.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "But go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel." The mission to the lost sheep of Israel is the first phase of the mission that will extend to "all nations" at 28:19. The Christological arc: Christ comes first to his own (John 1:11), gathers the remnant of Israel, and through the resurrection-commission extends the gathering to all peoples. The restriction here is temporary; its very definiteness ("do not go to Gentiles") anticipates the time when it will be lifted.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "And proclaim as you go, saying, \'The kingdom of heaven is at hand.\'" The disciples\' proclamation is verbatim what Jesus proclaimed at the opening of his ministry (4:17: "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand"). They are not inventing new content but broadcasting what they have received from him. The Christological significance: the kingdom is "at hand" because the King is present; the disciples\' proclamation extends the reach of his presence without replacing it.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Heal the sick, raise the dead, cleanse lepers, cast out demons. You received without paying; give without paying." The delegation of healing authority to the twelve extends the Isaianic fulfillment (Isa 35:5-6; 61:1-2) through his representatives. "You received without paying; give without paying" frames the mission as pure gift — grace extended without commercial logic. The Christological bearing: everything the disciples give has first been received from Christ; they are channels of his authority and grace, not independent sources.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "Acquire no gold or silver or copper for your belts, no bag for your journey, or two tunics or sandals or a staff, for the laborer deserves his food." The radical dependence-on-provision instruction echoes Elijah\'s wilderness provision (1 Kgs 17:4-6; 19:5-8) and the manna in the wilderness (Exod 16). The disciples travel in the pattern of Israel\'s wilderness journey, dependent on what their host-communities provide, trusting the provision of the one who sends them. Christ is the Lord who provides for those sent in his name.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "No bag for your journey, or two tunics or sandals or a staff, for the laborer deserves his food." The principle "the laborer deserves his food" is quoted by Paul (1 Tim 5:18; 1 Cor 9:14) as the basis for supporting gospel ministers. The instruction establishes a pattern of mutual dependence: the disciple gives freely; the community provides for the disciple. This is the kingdom economy — the inversion of market exchange, grounded in the prior grace of Christ who gave freely and was received by those who welcomed him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "And whatever town or village you enter, find out who is worthy in it and stay there until you depart." The peace-seeking pattern — finding a worthy household and staying — mirrors the prophetic pattern of Elijah and Elisha who were received by specific households (Zarephath, Shunam). The disciples are to discern receptivity rather than move promiscuously; concentrated presence with the receptive is more effective than superficial broadcast. Christ himself practiced concentrated presence (Capernaum as his base) alongside itinerant mission.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "As you enter the house, greet it. And if the house is worthy, let your peace come upon it, but if it is not worthy, let your peace return to you." The peace-greeting (<em>shalom</em>) is not merely a social convention but a covenantal blessing — the peace of the kingdom made available through the disciples\' presence. The conditional structure — peace given or withheld based on receptivity — mirrors the prophetic pattern of blessing and curse (Deut 28). The disciples carry and can withdraw the kingdom\'s peace.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "And if the house is worthy, let your peace come upon it, but if it is not worthy, let your peace return to you." The returning peace is not a failure of the mission but a protection of the messenger — those who carry kingdom-peace are not impoverished when it is rejected. The Christological bearing: Christ\'s own peace (John 14:27: "my peace I give to you") is the source from which the disciples\' peace flows; rejection of the disciples\' greeting is ultimately rejection of Christ\'s peace.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "And if anyone will not receive you or listen to your words, shake off the dust from your feet when you leave that house or town." The dust-shaking is a gesture of disassociation used by Jews returning from Gentile territory — the dust of impurity was shaken off at the border. By instructing Jewish disciples to use this gesture against Jewish towns, Jesus inverts the normal purity logic: towns that reject the kingdom-messengers are treated as if they are Gentile soil, outside the covenant people\'s boundaries. The rejection of the messengers is a rejection of the Lord who sends them.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, it will be more bearable on the day of judgment for the land of Sodom and Gomorrah than for that town." Christ pronounces eschatological judgment with absolute authority — "truly I say to you" is his own authenticating formula, not prophetic citation. The comparison to Sodom and Gomorrah (the paradigmatic judgment of Gen 19) escalates the severity: to reject the presence of the kingdom in the person of its messengers is worse than the sins that provoked the most famous divine judgment in OT history.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "Behold, I am sending you out as sheep in the midst of wolves, so be wise as serpents and innocent as doves." The "I am sending" (<em>egō apostellō</em>) is the apostolic commission formula — the disciples are <em>apostoloi</em> (sent ones) because Christ is the sender. The wisdom-and-innocence pair mirrors the Isaianic Servant who is both shrewd in navigating hostile contexts and undefiled by them (Isa 11:2-4). Christ himself navigated the wolves of Herodians, Pharisees, and Sadducees with the same combination.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "Beware of men, for they will deliver you over to courts and flog you in their synagogues." The persecution prediction — synagogue flogging and court appearances — anticipates both the disciples\' experience in Acts and Jesus\' own passion. The flogging in synagogues mirrors the forty-lashes-less-one of Deut 25:3, applied to those judged to have violated Torah. Jesus prepares the disciples to experience what he himself will experience; discipleship shares the master\'s path (10:24-25).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "And you will be dragged before governors and kings for my sake, to bear witness before them and the Gentiles." "For my sake" (<em>heneken emou</em>) frames the disciples\' persecution as participation in the rejection Christ himself will face. The appearance before governors and kings anticipates both Paul\'s missionary trials (Acts 25-26) and the mission to the Gentiles announced in 28:19. The suffering of the disciples will be the occasion for testimony — the very trial becomes the mission field.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "When they deliver you over, do not be anxious how you are to speak or what you are to say, for what you are to say will be given to you in that hour." The promise of the Spirit\'s supply in the moment of trial anticipates the Paraclete sayings of John 14:26 (the Spirit will teach you all things) and the Pentecost promise (Acts 1:8). The disciple does not prepare a defense but trusts in the provision of the one who sends them — the pattern of Jeremiah (Jer 1:6-9: "I will put my words in your mouth") enacted in the new covenant.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct revelation: "For it is not you who speak, but the Spirit of your Father speaking through you." The identification of the Spirit as the "Spirit of your Father" is a Trinitarian formulation embedded in a practical instruction. The disciples\' speech in persecution is the speech of the Spirit — which is the speech of Christ himself (John 16:13-15: the Spirit takes what is Christ\'s and declares it). The testimony of the persecuted disciple is the continuation of the mission of the Son through the Spirit.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "Brother will deliver brother over to death, and the father his child, and children will rise against parents and have them put to death." The eschatological family division mirrors Mic 7:6 ("for the son treats the father with contempt, the daughter rises up against her mother") — a text Jesus will cite explicitly in v.35. The breakdown of family bonds as the consequence of the kingdom\'s arrival is a recurring prophetic image for the eschatological crisis. Discipleship creates new loyalties that supersede biological family when the two conflict.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "And you will be hated by all for my name\'s sake. But the one who endures to the end will be saved." "For my name\'s sake" — the disciples\' persecution is entirely on account of their identification with Christ. The endurance promise ("he who endures to the end will be saved") is both encouragement and eschatological assurance: the one who holds to Christ through suffering will receive the salvation Christ brings. The passive "will be saved" is the divine passive — God saves through Christ those who persevere in him.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next, for truly, I say to you, you will not have gone through all the towns of Israel before the Son of Man comes." The difficult saying about the Son of Man\'s coming before the mission to Israel is complete has generated extensive discussion. Within its immediate context, it provides urgency without despair: the mission is time-bound, the Son of Man is coming, and the disciples should continue their work without being immobilized by persecution.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "A disciple is not above his teacher, nor a servant above his master." The disciple-teacher relationship defines the nature of Christian discipleship: the disciples\' calling is to become like their teacher (v.25). What Jesus suffered, they will suffer; what he proclaimed, they will proclaim; what he received, they will receive. The Christological bearing is foundational for the entire discourse: the disciples\' path is determined entirely by the path of the one they follow.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "It is enough for the disciple to be like his teacher, and the servant like his master. If they have called the master of the house Beelzebul, how much more will they malign those of his household." The comparison of discipleship to being a household servant positions the disciples as members of Christ\'s household — a family metaphor that Jesus will develop further (12:49-50: "whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother"). The "master of the house" (Beelzebul charge) anticipates the accusation of 12:24, making this passage a preview of the coming conflict.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "So have no fear of them, for nothing is covered that will not be revealed, or hidden that will not be known." The apocalyptic promise of disclosure — what is hidden will be revealed — cuts both ways: the disciples\' secret witness will be revealed as true, and the opposition\'s false accusations will be exposed as false. The eschatological judgment is simultaneously the vindication of the faithful and the exposure of the wicked. This is the foundation of fearlessness: the final verdict belongs to God, not to accusers.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "What I tell you in the dark, say in the light, and what you hear whispered, proclaim on the housetops." The instruction to broadcast publicly what Jesus teaches privately positions the disciples as the authorized transmitters of the kingdom\'s message. The progression from private instruction to public proclamation mirrors the prophetic pattern (Isa 48:6: "From this time forth I announce to you new things, hidden things that you have not known"). The disciples\' public proclamation is the extension of Christ\'s own proclamation.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "And do not fear those who kill the body but cannot kill the soul. Rather fear him who can destroy both soul and body in hell." The two fears are not equal: the fear of human killers is finite (body only); the fear of God is total (body and soul). The Christological frame: Christ himself will face the one who can kill the body (the human authorities) without fearing them, because he fears the Father and trusts in the resurrection. The disciples are called to the same fearlessness-before-humans grounded in reverence-before-God.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "Are not two sparrows sold for a penny? And not one of them will fall to the ground apart from your Father." The providential care of God extending to sparrows — the cheapest commodity in the market — is the foundation for the disciples\' fearlessness. The Father who numbers the sparrows is the same Father who sends his Son; the care that extends to the least creature is multiplied infinitely for those made in the divine image and redeemed by the Son\'s death.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "But even the hairs of your head are all numbered." The specific precision of divine care — individual hairs counted — intensifies the providential promise beyond what could be practically demonstrated. The hyperbole makes the theological point: God\'s care for those who are his is particular, not statistical. This is the character of the Father that Jesus reveals — a care that exceeds the most devoted human parenting, as 7:11 already argued from analogy.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "Fear not, therefore; you are of more value than many sparrows." The repeated "fear not" is the characteristic address of the divine presence throughout Scripture (1:20; 28:5, 10; Dan 10:12; Isa 41:10; 43:1). Jesus speaks the divine word of reassurance from his own authority. The valuation — "more than many sparrows" — is an understatement for rhetorical effect; the actual valuation is demonstrated in the cross: the Father gave the Son for each one of the ones he loves (John 3:16).</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "So everyone who acknowledges me before men, I also will acknowledge before my Father who is in heaven." The eschatological reciprocity — acknowledgment before humans answered by acknowledgment before the Father — positions Christ as the advocate before the divine court. The advocacy role is the OT intercessor role (Moses before YHWH, Exod 32:11-13) elevated to a unique status: Christ acknowledges those who acknowledge him, and does so before his own Father, as Son. This is the advocacy of John\'s Gospel (1 John 2:1: "we have an advocate with the Father").</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct revelation: "But whoever denies me before men, I also will deny before my Father who is in heaven." The negative case — denial before humans leading to denial before the Father — is the warning that Peter will violate (26:69-75) and then be restored from (John 21:15-17). The symmetry of acknowledgment/denial is not mechanical but relational: denial of Christ is a denial of the relationship itself; acknowledgment is the expression of genuine faith. The possibility of denial-and-restoration (Peter) and denial-without-restoration (Judas) shows that the pattern is not irreversible.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation: "Do not think that I came to bring peace to the earth. I did not come to bring peace, but a sword." The "I came" formula again (as in 5:17; 9:13) marks a divine-mission statement. The paradox of the Prince of Peace bringing a sword is resolved Christologically: the eschatological peace (Isa 9:6-7; Mic 5:5) comes through the crisis of decision that Christ\'s presence creates. The sword is the division between those who receive him and those who do not — a division that cuts through every social unit, including families.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "For I have come to set a man against his father, and a daughter against her mother, and a daughter-in-law against her mother-in-law." The explicit quotation of Mic 7:6 positions Jesus\' mission as the fulfillment of the eschatological crisis Micah described. In its original context, Mic 7:6 described the moral collapse of Israelite society; Jesus applies it to the crisis his own coming creates. The quotation is a fulfillment-claim: the situation Micah described as a coming judgment is now occurring because the kingdom has arrived.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "And a person\'s enemies will be those of his own household." The inversion of household solidarity — the home as the site of opposition rather than support — is the sociological consequence of the division Mic 7:6 describes. The disciples who follow Jesus will experience this division; Jesus himself will experience it (his brothers do not believe in him during his ministry, John 7:5). The suffering of family rejection is a participation in what the Son of God himself endures.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "Whoever loves father or mother more than me is not worthy of me, and whoever loves son or daughter more than me is not worthy of me." The love-priority claim is the most explicit statement of Christ\'s supremacy over all other loyalties in Matthew. The worthiness standard (<em>axios</em>) is specifically about relationship to him — not about moral performance but about the primacy of one\'s devotion. Only God could legitimately claim priority over the love owed to parents and children; Jesus claims it as his own prerogative, the same claim that constitutes the Great Commandment applied to himself.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "And whoever does not take his cross and follow me is not worthy of me." The cross-bearing instruction is made before the crucifixion — the disciples are being prepared for a path that leads where Jesus\' path leads. The cross is here a metaphor for the shameful, public, life-ending walk of the condemned (later given its literal content by Jesus\' passion). Discipleship is not addition to one\'s existing life but the embrace of its loss — which is the logic Paul will develop in Phil 3:7-11.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "Whoever finds his life will lose it, and whoever loses his life for my sake will find it." The life-losing/life-finding paradox is the Christological inversion at the heart of the Gospel. The one who clings to his natural life loses the eternal life Christ brings; the one who surrenders it "for my sake" finds the life that cannot be lost. The Christological warrant: Jesus himself lost his life and found it — the resurrection is the demonstration of the principle he teaches. "For my sake" ties the disciples\' loss to the specific relation with Christ that makes it salvific rather than merely heroic.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A direct revelation: "Whoever receives you receives me, and whoever receives me receives him who sent me." The chain of reception — disciple/Christ/Father — is the most explicit identification of Christ with the Father\'s mission in this discourse. To receive the disciples is to receive Christ; to receive Christ is to receive the Father who sent him. This is the Johannine mutual indwelling (John 13:20; 14:9-11) stated in Synoptic form: the disciples are extensions of Christ\'s presence, and Christ is the presence of the Father among humanity.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "The one who receives a prophet because he is a prophet will receive a prophet\'s reward, and the one who receives a righteous person because he is righteous will receive a righteous person\'s reward." The reward-structure of reception anticipates the judgment of 25:31-46, where care for "the least of these" is care for Christ himself. The "prophet\'s reward" and "righteous person\'s reward" are defined by the character of the gift: those who receive the kingdom\'s messengers participate in the kingdom\'s blessings.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct revelation: "And whoever gives one of these little ones even a cup of cold water because he is a disciple, truly, I say to you, he will by no means lose his reward." The "little ones" (<em>mikrōn toutōn</em>) are the disciples — those who are small in the world\'s estimation but precious to Christ. The cup of cold water — the smallest possible act of hospitality — done "because he is a disciple" (i.e., done in recognition of the disciple\'s identity as Christ\'s representative) receives its full reward. The smallest act of reception toward the smallest disciple is registered before the Father who sees all things (6:4, 6, 18). The discourse closes with the logic of 10:40: the disciple carries Christ\'s presence, and even the smallest kindness to them is kindness to him.</p>'
  }
}

